This was an odd observation. This bird flew in low over the yard. Then it circled back right through the trees, not above them. Then it landed on a utility pole, did several bill wipes, fluffed its feathers, looked around, bill wiped, spent some more time looking around, and left after about four minutes. I have seen Turkey Vultures fly over, but have never had one land as this one did. Vultures will roost in trees in town during the migration. This bird wasn't migrating or roosting.

Observation Details: I saw the weirdest behavior of three Turkey vultures in a field. Two of them were in an aggressive fight and the third one was close with head down initially. The fighting went on for a while, followed by the two hopping/walking energetically toward the third bird. Then all three of them (with the third bird kind of hanging back), sort of marched around the area together, not really in a chase, but a kind of aggressive energy, like trying to shoulder the other guy out of the way. And then a little more aggression with the wings of one toward the other (from behind).

Media notes: Interactuando, contacto entre ellos y acicalamiento. Se observa que a veces cuando se acicalan o tienen contacto el individuo que se acerca o frota su cabeza contra el cuerpo del otro utiliza su membrana nictitante
Observation Details: Los encontré otra vez en la jardinera del edificio de a lado posados, mirando a traves de la ventana, no sé si descansando o esperando ver al perro peruano sin cola que vive en ese departamento y quizas les llama la atención. Durante este tiempo se asicalaron cada uno y hubieron momentos que lo hicieron entre ellos, se rascaron la cabeza con la pata, se estiraron, interactuaron entre ellos. Durante todo este tiempo se dieron cuenta de mi presencia, al inicio fueron atentos a mis movimientos, a pesar que me movia poco, lento y lo más silenciosamente posible detras de la cortina de mi ventana, y un momento sin querer los asusté y a las 9h11 volaron al techo de mi edificio, solo se fueron de mi vista por unos minutos. A las 9h25 volvió primero 1 y casi inmediatamente se acercó a la ventana y como que la picó como quererla abrir, luego volvio el otro pero ya más confiados de mi presencia, porque no se mostraron curiosos de mi esta vez ya que interactuaron bastante entre ellos, parece ser una pareja. En un momento este segundo hizo lo mismo que el primero pero del otro borde de la ventana como picarla suavemente o miraba su reflejo. Se fueron a las 9h44 y no volvieron más por hoy

This adult Turkey Vulture was with a group of five, down on the ground in a plowed field, encircling a dead Woodchuck.  It was a somewhat chilly morning, with the temperature at 50 degrees F., which is pretty cold for the first official day of Summer!  Maybe that is why this individual vulture was thermoregulating by spreading its wings toward the rising sun, in an effort to absorb some heat.  They say that all vultures engage in this behavior.  Notice this individual is molting its flight feathers, and symmetrically on both wings.  On both wings, primaries #1 through primaries #6 are new, with #6 only being half grown in.  The outer three primaries are old, and sun-faded brown.  This vulture's wing symmetry, even during a molt, enables this highly-efficient soaring bird, to fly more efficiently.
Possible nesting site in rocky outcropping? Photos.

Atlas square 13UDQ57 - Old pump house (private property)
Observation Details: An adult Vulture was circling around the whole time we were here.  We went into the upper loft of this small old wooden shed and there on the south side on the floor were two young Turkey Vultures.  They looked to me like they had several more weeks before they were ready to fledge the nest site.  At one point, they started to hiss when obviously we approached too close for their liking.  I obtained one decent photograph of the young and several of the old pump house itself.  The owner of the property, who was with me at the time, told me a pair of Turkey Vulture had been nesting in this location for the last two or three breeding seasons.
